{{Short description|Similar DNA, RNA or protein sequences within genomes or among species}}
{{Hatnote|Compare [[sequence motif]]s and [[protein domain]]s.}}
[[File:Histone Alignment.png|thumb|400px|A multiple [[sequence alignment]] of five mammalian [[histone H1]] proteins <br />
Sequences are the [[Amino acid#Table of standard amino acid abbreviations and side chain properties|amino acids]] for residues 120-180 of the proteins. Residues that are conserved across all sequences are highlighted in grey. Below each site (i.e., position) of the protein sequence alignment is a key denoting conserved sites (*), sites with [[conservative replacement]]s (:), sites with semi-conservative replacements (.), and sites with [[segregating site|non-conservative replacements]] ( ).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ebi.ac.uk/Tools/msa/clustalw2/help/faq.html#23|website=Clustal |title= Clustal FAQ #Symbols|accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref>]]

In [[evolutionary biology]], '''conserved sequences''' are identical or similar [[Sequence (biology)|sequences]] in [[nucleic acid]]s ([[DNA sequence|DNA]] and [[RNA]]) or [[peptide sequence|proteins]] across species ([[homology (biology)#Orthology|orthologous sequences]]), or within a [[genome]] ([[homology (biology)#Paralogy|paralogous sequences]]), or between donor and receptor taxa ([[Sequence homology#Xenology|xenologous sequences]]). Conservation indicates that a sequence has been maintained by [[natural selection]].

A highly conserved sequence is one that has remained relatively unchanged far back up the [[phylogenetic tree]], and hence far back in [[geological time]]. Examples of highly conserved sequences include the [[Ribosomal RNA|RNA components]] of [[ribosome]]s present in all [[domain (biology)|domain]]s of life, the [[homeobox]] sequences widespread amongst [[Eukaryotes]], and the [[tmRNA]] in [[Bacteria]]. The study of sequence conservation overlaps with the fields of [[genomics]], [[proteomics]], [[evolutionary biology]], [[phylogenetics]], [[bioinformatics]] and [[mathematics]].

==History==
{{See also|History of molecular evolution}}

The discovery of the role of [[DNA#History of DNA research|DNA in inheritance]], and observations by [[Frederick Sanger]] of variation between animal [[insulin]]s in 1949,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sanger |first1=F. |title=Species Differences in Insulins |journal=Nature |date=24 September 1949 |volume=164 |issue=4169 |pages=529 |doi=10.1038/164529a0}}</ref> prompted early molecular biologists to study [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomy]] from a molecular perspective.<ref name="ReferenceA">{{cite journal |last1=Marmur |first1=J |last2=Falkow |first2=S |last3=Mandel |first3=M |title=New Approaches to Bacterial Taxonomy |journal=Annual Review of Microbiology |date=October 1963 |volume=17 |issue=1 |pages=329–372 |doi=10.1146/annurev.mi.17.100163.001553|pmid=14147455 }}</ref><ref name="ReferenceB">{{cite journal |last1=Pace |first1=N. R. |last2=Sapp |first2=J. |last3=Goldenfeld |first3=N. |title=Phylogeny and beyond: Scientific, historical, and conceptual significance of the first tree of life |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |date=17 January 2012 |volume=109 |issue=4 |pages=1011–1018 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1109716109|pmid=22308526 |pmc=3268332 }}</ref> Studies in the 1960s used [[DNA-DNA hybridization|DNA hybridization]] and protein cross-reactivity techniques to measure similarity between known [[orthologous]] proteins, such as [[hemoglobin]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Zuckerlandl |first1=Emile |author1link=Emile Zuckerkandl |last2=Pauling |first2=Linus B. |author2link=Linus Pauling |title=Molecular disease, evolution, and genetic heterogeneity |journal=Horizons in Biochemistry |date=1962 |pages=189–225}}</ref> and [[Cytochrome C]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Margoliash |first1=E |title=PRIMARY STRUCTURE AND EVOLUTION OF CYTOCHROME C |journal=Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A |date=Oct 1963 |volume=50 |issue=4 |pages=672–679 |doi=10.1073/pnas.50.4.672|pmid=14077496 |pmc=221244 }}</ref> In 1965, [[Emile Zuckerkandl|Émile Zuckerkandl]] and [[Linus Pauling]] introduced the concept of the [[molecular clock]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Zuckerkandl |first1=E |last2=Pauling |first2=LB |title=Evolutionary Divergence and Convergence in Proteins |journal=Evolving Genes and Proteins |date=1965 |pages=96–166 |doi=10.1016/B978-1-4832-2734-4.50017-6|isbn=9781483227344 }}</ref> proposing that steady rates of mutation could be used to estimate the time since two organisms [[Divergent evolution|diverged]]. While initial phylogenies closely matched the [[fossil record]], observations that some genes appeared to evolve at different rates led to the development of theories of [[molecular evolution]].<ref name="ReferenceA"/><ref name="ReferenceB"/> [[Margaret Oakley Dayhoff|Margaret Dayhoff's]] 1966 comparison of [[ferrodoxin]] sequences showed that [[natural selection]] would act to conserve and optimise protein sequences essential to life.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Eck |first1=R. V. |last2=Dayhoff |first2=M. O. |title=Evolution of the Structure of Ferredoxin Based on Living Relics of Primitive Amino Acid Sequences |journal=Science |date=15 April 1966 |volume=152 |issue=3720 |pages=363–366 |doi=10.1126/science.152.3720.363|pmid=17775169 }}</ref>

==Mechanisms==

{{See also| Natural selection|Neutral theory of molecular evolution}}

Over many generations, nucleic acid sequences in the [[genome]] of an [[Lineage (evolution)|evolutionary lineage]] can gradually change over time due to random mutations and [[Deletion (genetics)|deletions]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kimura|first1=M|title=Evolutionary Rate at the Molecular Level|journal=Nature|date=17 February 1968|volume=217|issue=5129|pages=624–626|doi=10.1038/217624a0}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=King|first1=J. L.|last2=Jukes|first2=T. H.|title=Non-Darwinian Evolution|journal=Science|date=16 May 1969|volume=164|issue=3881|pages=788–798|doi=10.1126/science.164.3881.788}}</ref> Sequences may also recombine or be deleted due to [[chromosomal rearrangement]]s. Conserved sequences are sequences which persist in the genome despite such forces, and have slower rates of mutation than the background mutation rate.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kimura|first1=M|last2=Ohta|first2=T|title=On Some Principles Governing Molecular Evolution|journal=Proc Natl Acad Sci USA|date=1974|volume=71|issue=7|pages=2848–2852|doi=10.1073/pnas.71.7.2848| pmc=388569 |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC388569/pdf/pnas00060-0262.pdf|pmid=4527913}}</ref>

Conservation can occur in [[Coding region|coding]] and [[Noncoding DNA|non-coding]] nucleic acid sequences. Highly conserved DNA sequences are thought to have functional value, although the role for many highly conserved non-coding DNA sequences is poorly understood. The extent to which a sequence is conserved can be affected by varying [[Evolutionary pressure|selection pressures]], its [[Robustness (evolution)|robustness]] to mutation, [[Population genetics|population size]] and [[genetic drift]]. Many functional sequences are also [[Modularity (biology)|modular]], containing regions which may be subject to independent [[Evolutionary pressure|selection pressures]], such as [[Protein domain#Domains as evolutionary modules|protein domains]].{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}

===Coding sequence===
In coding sequences, the nucleic acid and amino acid sequence may be conserved to different extents, as the degeneracy of the [[genetic code]] means that [[Synonymous substitution|synonymous mutations]] in a coding sequence do not affect the amino acid sequence of its protein product.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}

Amino acid sequences can be conserved to maintain the [[Protein structure|structure]] or function of a protein or domain. Conserved proteins undergo fewer [[amino acid replacement]]s, or are more likely to [[conservative mutation|substitute amino acids with similar biochemical properties]]. Within a sequence, amino acids that are important for [[protein folding|folding]], structural stability, or that form a [[binding site]] may be more highly conserved.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}

The nucleic acid sequence of a protein coding gene may also be conserved by other selective pressures. The [[codon usage bias]] in some organisms may restrict the types of synonymous mutations in a sequence. Nucleic acid sequences that cause [[Nucleic acid secondary structure|secondary structure]] in the mRNA of a coding gene may be selected against, as some structures may negatively affect translation, or conserved where the mRNA also acts as a functional non-coding RNA.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Chamary|first1=JV|last2=Hurst|first2=Laurence D|title=Evidence for selection on synonymous mutations affecting stability of mRNA secondary structure in mammals|journal=Genome Biology|date=2005|volume=6|issue=9|pages=R75|doi=10.1186/gb-2005-6-9-r75|pmid=16168082|pmc=1242210}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wadler|first1=C. S.|last2=Vanderpool|first2=C. K.|title=A dual function for a bacterial small RNA: SgrS performs base pairing-dependent regulation and encodes a functional polypeptide|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|date=27 November 2007|volume=104|issue=51|pages=20454–20459|doi=10.1073/pnas.0708102104|pmid=18042713|pmc=2154452}}</ref>

===Non-coding===
{{See also |Conserved non-coding sequence}}

Non-coding sequences important for [[gene regulation]], such as the binding or recognition sites of [[Ribosome-binding site|ribosomes]] and [[transcription factor]]s, may be conserved within a genome. For example, the [[promoter (genetics)|promoter]] of a conserved gene or [[operon]] may also be conserved. As with proteins, nucleic acids that are important for the structure and function of [[non-coding RNA]] (ncRNA) can also be conserved. However, sequence conservation in ncRNAs is generally poor compared to protein-coding sequences, and [[base pairs]] that contribute to structure or function are often conserved instead.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Johnsson |first1=Per |last2=Lipovich |first2=Leonard |last3=Grandér |first3=Dan |last4=Morris |first4=Kevin V. |title=Evolutionary conservation of long non-coding RNAs; sequence, structure, function |journal=Biochimica et Biophysica Acta (BBA) - General Subjects |date=March 2014 |volume=1840 |issue=3 |pages=1063–1071 |doi=10.1016/j.bbagen.2013.10.035|pmid=24184936 |pmc=3909678 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Freyhult |first1=E. K. |last2=Bollback |first2=J. P. |last3=Gardner |first3=P. P. |title=Exploring genomic dark matter: A critical assessment of the performance of homology search methods on noncoding RNA |journal=Genome Research |date=6 December 2006 |volume=17 |issue=1 |pages=117–125 |doi=10.1101/gr.5890907|pmid=17151342 |pmc=1716261 }}</ref>

==Identification==
{{See also|Sequence alignment}}
Conserved sequences are typically identified by [[bioinformatics]] approaches based on [[sequence alignment]]. Advances in [[DNA sequencing#High-throughput methods|high-throughput DNA sequencing]] and [[protein mass spectrometry]] has substantially increased the availability of protein sequences and whole genomes for comparison since the early 2000s.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}

===Homology search===

Conserved sequences may be identified by [[Homology (biology)|homology]] search, using tools such as [[BLAST]], [[HMMER]] and Infernal.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Nawrocki |first1=E. P. |last2=Eddy |first2=S. R. |title=Infernal 1.1: 100-fold faster RNA homology searches |journal=Bioinformatics |date=4 September 2013 |volume=29 |issue=22 |pages=2933–2935 |doi=10.1093/bioinformatics/btt509|pmid=24008419 |pmc=3810854 }}</ref> Homology search tools may take an individual nucleic acid or protein sequence as input, or use statistical models generated from [[multiple sequence alignment]]s of known related sequences. Statistical models such as [[Hidden Markov model|profile-HMMs]], and RNA covariance models which also incorporate structural information,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Eddy |first1=SR|last2=Durbin |first2=R |title=RNA sequence analysis using covariance models. |journal=Nucleic Acids Research|date=11 June 1994|volume=22 |issue=11 |pages=2079–88 |pmid=8029015 |doi=10.1093/nar/22.11.2079 |pmc=308124}}</ref> can be helpful when searching for more distantly related sequences. Input sequences are then aligned against a database of sequences from related individuals or other species. The resulting alignments are then scored based on the number of matching amino acids or bases, and the number of gaps or deletions generated by the alignment. Acceptable conservative substitutions may be identified using substitution matrices such as [[Point accepted mutation|PAM]] and [[BLOSUM]]. Highly scoring alignments are assumed to be from homologous sequences. The conservation of a sequence may then be inferred by detection of highly similar homologs over a broad phylogenetic range.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}

===Multiple sequence alignment===
[[File:LexA gram positive bacteria sequence logo.png|400px|thumb|right|A sequence logo for the LexA-binding motif of [[gram-positive]] bacteria. As the [[adenosine]] at position 5 is highly conserved, it appears larger than other characters.<ref name="Weblogo"/>]]

Multiple sequence alignments can be used to visualise conserved sequences. The [[clustal|CLUSTAL]] format includes a plain-text key to annotate conserved columns of the alignment, denoting conserved sequence (*), conservative mutations (:), semi-conservative mutations (.), and non-conservative mutations ( )<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ebi.ac.uk/Tools/msa/clustalw2/help/faq.html#23 |website=Clustal |title=Clustal FAQ #Symbols |accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref> Sequence logos can also show conserved sequence by representing the proportions of characters at each point in the alignment by height.<ref name="Weblogo">{{cite web |title=Weblogo |url=http://weblogo.berkeley.edu/ |publisher=UC Berkeley |accessdate=30 December 2017}}</ref>

===Genome alignment=== 
[[File:ECR_browser_showing_conserved_OTX2_gene_in_vertebrates.png|thumb|500px|right|This image from the ECR browser<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ecrbrowser.dcode.org |title=ECR Browser |website=ECR Browser |accessdate=9 January 2018}}</ref> shows the result of aligning different vertebrate genomes to the human genome at the conserved [[Orthodenticle homeobox 2|OTX2]] gene. Top: Gene annotations of [[exon]]s and [[intron]]s of the OTX2 gene. For each genome, sequence similarity (%) compared to the human genome is plotted. Tracks show the [[zebrafish]], [[dog]], [[chicken]], [[Xenopus tropicalis|western clawed frog]], [[opossum]], [[mouse]], [[rhesus macaque]] and [[chimpanzee]] genomes. The peaks show regions of high sequence similarity across all genomes, showing that this sequence is highly conserved.]]

Whole genome alignments (WGAs) may also be used to identify highly conserved regions across species. Currently the accuracy and [[scalability]] of WGA tools remains limited due to the computational complexity of dealing with rearrangements, repeat regions and the large size of many eukaryotic genomes.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Earl |first1=Dent |last2=Nguyen |first2=Ngan |last3=Hickey |first3=Glenn |last4=Harris |first4=Robert S. |last5=Fitzgerald |first5=Stephen |last6=Beal |first6=Kathryn |last7=Seledtsov |first7=Igor |last8=Molodtsov |first8=Vladimir |last9=Raney |first9=Brian J. |last10=Clawson |first10=Hiram |last11=Kim |first11=Jaebum |last12=Kemena |first12=Carsten |last13=Chang |first13=Jia-Ming |last14=Erb |first14=Ionas |last15=Poliakov |first15=Alexander |last16=Hou |first16=Minmei |last17=Herrero |first17=Javier |last18=Kent |first18=William James |last19=Solovyev |first19=Victor |last20=Darling |first20=Aaron E. |last21=Ma |first21=Jian |last22=Notredame |first22=Cedric |last23=Brudno |first23=Michael |last24=Dubchak |first24=Inna |last25=Haussler |first25=David |last26=Paten |first26=Benedict |title=Alignathon: a competitive assessment of whole-genome alignment methods |journal=Genome Research |date=December 2014 |volume=24 |issue=12 |pages=2077–2089 |doi=10.1101/gr.174920.114|pmid=25273068 |pmc=4248324 }}</ref> However, WGAs of 30 or more closely related bacteria (prokaryotes) are now increasingly feasible.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Rouli |first1=L. |last2=Merhej |first2=V. |last3=Fournier |first3=P.-E. |last4=Raoult |first4=D. |title=The bacterial pangenome as a new tool for analysing pathogenic bacteria |journal=New Microbes and New Infections |date=September 2015 |volume=7 |pages=72–85 |doi=10.1016/j.nmni.2015.06.005|pmid=26442149 |pmc=4552756 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Méric |first1=Guillaume |last2=Yahara |first2=Koji |last3=Mageiros |first3=Leonardos |last4=Pascoe |first4=Ben |last5=Maiden |first5=Martin C. J. |last6=Jolley |first6=Keith A. |last7=Sheppard |first7=Samuel K. |last8=Bereswill |first8=Stefan |title=A Reference Pan-Genome Approach to Comparative Bacterial Genomics: Identification of Novel Epidemiological Markers in Pathogenic Campylobacter |journal=PLoS ONE |date=27 March 2014 |volume=9 |issue=3 |pages=e92798 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0092798|pmid=24676150 |pmc=3968026 }}</ref>

===Scoring systems===

Other approaches use measurements of conservation based on [[Statistical hypothesis testing|statistical tests]] that attempt to identify sequences which mutate differently to an expected background (neutral) mutation rate.

The GERP (Genomic Evolutionary Rate Profiling) framework scores conservation of genetic sequences across species. This approach estimates the rate of neutral mutation in a set of species from a multiple sequence alignment, and then identifies regions of the sequence that exhibit fewer mutations than expected. These regions are then assigned scores based on the difference between the observed mutation rate and expected background mutation rate. A high GERP score then indicates a highly conserved sequence.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cooper |first1=G. M. |title=Distribution and intensity of constraint in mammalian genomic sequence |journal=Genome Research |date=17 June 2005 |volume=15 |issue=7 |pages=901–913 |doi=10.1101/gr.3577405|pmid=15965027 |pmc=1172034 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://mendel.stanford.edu/SidowLab/downloads/gerp/|title=Sidow Lab - GERP}}</ref>

Other approaches such as PhyloP and PhyloHMM incorporate [[Phylogenetic comparative methods|statistical phylogenetics]] methods to compare [[probability distribution]]s of substitution rates, which allows the detection of both conservation and accelerated mutation. First, a background probability distribution is generated of the number of substitutions expected to occur for a column in a multiple sequence alignment, based on a [[phylogenetic tree]]. The estimated evolutionary relationships between the species of interest are used to calculate the significance of any substitutions (i.e. a substitution between two closely related species may be less likely to occur than distantly related ones, and therefore more significant). To detect conservation, a probability distribution is calculated for a subset of the multiple sequence alignment, and compared to the background distribution using a statistical test such as a [[likelihood-ratio test]] or [[score test]]. [[P-value]]s generated from comparing the two distributions are then used to identify conserved regions. PhyloHMM uses [[hidden markov model]]s to generate probability distributions. The PhyloP software package compares probability distributions using a [[likelihood-ratio test]] or [[score test]], as well as using a GERP-like scoring system.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pollard |first1=K. S. |last2=Hubisz |first2=M. J. |last3=Rosenbloom |first3=K. R. |last4=Siepel |first4=A. |title=Detection of nonneutral substitution rates on mammalian phylogenies |journal=Genome Research |date=26 October 2009 |volume=20 |issue=1 |pages=110–121 |doi=10.1101/gr.097857.109|pmid=19858363 |pmc=2798823 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://compgen.cshl.edu/phast/index.php|title=PHAST: Home}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fan |first1=Xiaodan |last2=Zhu |first2=Jun |last3=Schadt |first3=Eric E |last4=Liu |first4=Jun S |title=Statistical power of phylo-HMM for evolutionarily conserved element detection |journal=BMC Bioinformatics |date=2007 |volume=8 |issue=1 |pages=374 |doi=10.1186/1471-2105-8-374|pmid=17919331 |pmc=2194792 }}</ref>

==Extreme conservation==

===Ultra-conserved elements===

[[Ultra-conserved element]]s or UCEs are sequences that are highly similar or identical across multiple [[Taxonomic rank|taxonomic groupings]]. These were first discovered in [[vertebrates]],<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bejerano |first1=G. |title=Ultraconserved Elements in the Human Genome |journal=Science |date=28 May 2004 |volume=304 |issue=5675 |pages=1321–1325 |doi=10.1126/science.1098119|pmid=15131266 |citeseerx=10.1.1.380.9305 }}</ref> and have subsequently been identified within widely-differing taxa.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Siepel |first1=A. |title=Evolutionarily conserved elements in vertebrate, insect, worm, and yeast genomes |journal=Genome Research |date=1 August 2005 |volume=15 |issue=8 |pages=1034–1050 |doi=10.1101/gr.3715005|pmid=16024819 |pmc=1182216 }}</ref> While the origin and function of UCEs are poorly understood,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Harmston |first1=N. |last2=Baresic |first2=A. |last3=Lenhard |first3=B. |title=The mystery of extreme non-coding conservation |journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences |date=11 November 2013 |volume=368 |issue=1632 |pages=20130021 |doi=10.1098/rstb.2013.0021|pmid=24218634 |pmc=3826495 }}</ref> they have been used to investigate deep-time divergences in [[amniote]]s,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Faircloth |first1=B. C. |last2=McCormack |first2=J. E. |last3=Crawford |first3=N. G. |last4=Harvey |first4=M. G. |last5=Brumfield |first5=R. T. |last6=Glenn |first6=T. C. |title=Ultraconserved Elements Anchor Thousands of Genetic Markers Spanning Multiple Evolutionary Timescales |journal=Systematic Biology |date=9 January 2012 |volume=61 |issue=5 |pages=717–726 |doi=10.1093/sysbio/sys004|pmid=22232343 }}</ref> [[insects]],<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Faircloth |first1=Brant C. |last2=Branstetter |first2=Michael G. |last3=White |first3=Noor D. |last4=Brady |first4=Seán G. |title=Target enrichment of ultraconserved elements from arthropods provides a genomic perspective on relationships among Hymenoptera |journal=Molecular Ecology Resources |date=May 2015 |volume=15 |issue=3 |pages=489–501 |doi=10.1111/1755-0998.12328|pmid=25207863 |pmc=4407909 }}</ref> and between [[animals]] and [[plants]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Reneker |first1=J. |last2=Lyons |first2=E. |last3=Conant |first3=G. C. |last4=Pires |first4=J. C. |last5=Freeling |first5=M. |last6=Shyu |first6=C.-R. |last7=Korkin |first7=D. |title=Long identical multispecies elements in plant and animal genomes |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |date=10 April 2012 |volume=109 |issue=19 |pages=E1183–E1191 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1121356109|pmid=22496592 |pmc=3358895 }}</ref>

===Universally conserved genes===
The most highly conserved genes are those that can be found in all organisms. These consist mainly of the [[ncRNA]]s and proteins required for [[Transcription (biology)|transcription]] and [[Translation (biology)|translation]], which are assumed to have been conserved from the [[last universal common ancestor]] of all life.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Isenbarger |first1=Thomas A. |last2=Carr |first2=Christopher E. |last3=Johnson |first3=Sarah Stewart |last4=Finney |first4=Michael |last5=Church |first5=George M. |last6=Gilbert |first6=Walter |last7=Zuber |first7=Maria T. |last8=Ruvkun |first8=Gary |title=The Most Conserved Genome Segments for Life Detection on Earth and Other Planets |journal=Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres |date=14 October 2008 |volume=38 |issue=6 |pages=517–533 |doi=10.1007/s11084-008-9148-z|pmid=18853276 }}</ref>

Genes or gene families that have been found to be universally conserved include [[GTP-binding elongation factor family, EF-Tu/EF-1A subfamily|GTP-binding elongation factors]], [[METAP2|Methionine aminopeptidase 2]], [[Serine hydroxymethyltransferase]], and [[ATP-binding cassette transporter|ATP transporters]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Harris |first1=J. K. |title=The Genetic Core of the Universal Ancestor |journal=Genome Research |date=12 February 2003 |volume=13 |issue=3 |pages=407–412 |doi=10.1101/gr.652803|pmid=12618371 |pmc=430263 }}</ref> Components of the transcription machinery, such as [[RNA polymerase]] and [[helicase]]s, and of the translation machinery, such as [[ribosomal RNA]]s, [[Transfer RNA|tRNAs]] and [[ribosomal protein]]s are also universally conserved.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ban |first1=Nenad |last2=Beckmann |first2=Roland |last3=Cate |first3=Jamie HD |last4=Dinman |first4=Jonathan D |last5=Dragon |first5=François |last6=Ellis |first6=Steven R |last7=Lafontaine |first7=Denis LJ |last8=Lindahl |first8=Lasse |last9=Liljas |first9=Anders |last10=Lipton |first10=Jeffrey M |last11=McAlear |first11=Michael A |last12=Moore |first12=Peter B |last13=Noller |first13=Harry F |last14=Ortega |first14=Joaquin |last15=Panse |first15=Vikram Govind |last16=Ramakrishnan |first16=V |last17=Spahn |first17=Christian MT |last18=Steitz |first18=Thomas A |last19=Tchorzewski |first19=Marek |last20=Tollervey |first20=David |last21=Warren |first21=Alan J |last22=Williamson |first22=James R |last23=Wilson |first23=Daniel |last24=Yonath |first24=Ada |last25=Yusupov |first25=Marat |title=A new system for naming ribosomal proteins |journal=Current Opinion in Structural Biology |date=February 2014 |volume=24 |pages=165–169 |doi=10.1016/j.sbi.2014.01.002|pmid=24524803 |pmc=4358319 }}</ref>

== Applications ==

===Phylogenetics and taxonomy===

Sets of conserved sequences are often used for generating [[phylogenetic tree]]s, as it can be assumed that organisms with similar sequences are closely related.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gadagkar|first1=Sudhindra R.|last2=Rosenberg|first2=Michael S.|last3=Kumar|first3=Sudhir|title=Inferring species phylogenies from multiple genes: Concatenated sequence tree versus consensus gene tree|journal=Journal of Experimental Zoology Part B: Molecular and Developmental Evolution|date=15 January 2005|volume=304B|issue=1|pages=64–74|doi=10.1002/jez.b.21026|pmid=15593277}}</ref> The choice of sequences may vary depending on the taxonomic scope of the study. For example, the most highly conserved genes such as the 16S RNA and other ribosomal sequences are useful for reconstructing deep phylogenetic relationships and identifying bacterial [[phylum|phyla]] in [[metagenomics]] studies.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ludwig|first1=W|last2=Schleifer|first2=KH|title=Bacterial phylogeny based on 16S and 23S rRNA sequence analysis.|journal=FEMS Microbiology Reviews|date=October 1994|volume=15|issue=2–3|pages=155–73|pmid=7524576|doi=10.1111/j.1574-6976.1994.tb00132.x}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hug|first1=Laura A.|last2=Baker|first2=Brett J.|last3=Anantharaman|first3=Karthik|last4=Brown|first4=Christopher T.|last5=Probst|first5=Alexander J.|last6=Castelle|first6=Cindy J.|last7=Butterfield|first7=Cristina N.|last8=Hernsdorf|first8=Alex W.|last9=Amano|first9=Yuki|last10=Ise|first10=Kotaro|last11=Suzuki|first11=Yohey|last12=Dudek|first12=Natasha|last13=Relman|first13=David A.|last14=Finstad|first14=Kari M.|last15=Amundson|first15=Ronald|last16=Thomas|first16=Brian C.|last17=Banfield|first17=Jillian F.|title=A new view of the tree of life|journal=Nature Microbiology|date=11 April 2016|volume=1|issue=5|pages=16048|doi=10.1038/nmicrobiol.2016.48|pmid=27572647}}</ref> Sequences that are conserved within a [[clade]] but undergo some mutations, such as [[housekeeping gene]]s, can be used to study species relationships.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Zhang|first1=Liqing|last2=Li|first2=Wen-Hsiung|title=Mammalian Housekeeping Genes Evolve More Slowly than Tissue-Specific Genes|journal=Molecular Biology and Evolution|date=February 2004|volume=21|issue=2|pages=236–239|doi=10.1093/molbev/msh010|pmid=14595094}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Clermont|first1=O.|last2=Bonacorsi|first2=S.|last3=Bingen|first3=E.|title=Rapid and Simple Determination of the Escherichia coli Phylogenetic Group|journal=Applied and Environmental Microbiology|date=1 October 2000|volume=66|issue=10|pages=4555–4558|doi=10.1128/AEM.66.10.4555-4558.2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kullberg|first1=Morgan|last2=Nilsson|first2=Maria A.|last3=Arnason|first3=Ulfur|last4=Harley|first4=Eric H.|last5=Janke|first5=Axel|title=Housekeeping Genes for Phylogenetic Analysis of Eutherian Relationships|journal=Molecular Biology and Evolution|date=August 2006|volume=23|issue=8|pages=1493–1503|doi=10.1093/molbev/msl027|pmid=16751257}}</ref> The [[internal transcribed spacer]] (ITS) region, which is required for spacing conserved rRNA genes but undergoes rapid evolution, is commonly used to classify [[fungi]] and strains of rapidly evolving bacteria.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Schoch|first1=C. L.|last2=Seifert|first2=K. A.|last3=Huhndorf|first3=S.|last4=Robert|first4=V.|last5=Spouge|first5=J. L.|last6=Levesque|first6=C. A.|last7=Chen|first7=W.|last8=Bolchacova|first8=E.|last9=Voigt|first9=K.|last10=Crous|first10=P. W.|last11=Miller|first11=A. N.|last12=Wingfield|first12=M. J.|last13=Aime|first13=M. C.|last14=An|first14=K.-D.|last15=Bai|first15=F.-Y.|last16=Barreto|first16=R. W.|last17=Begerow|first17=D.|last18=Bergeron|first18=M.-J.|last19=Blackwell|first19=M.|last20=Boekhout|first20=T.|last21=Bogale|first21=M.|last22=Boonyuen|first22=N.|last23=Burgaz|first23=A. R.|last24=Buyck|first24=B.|last25=Cai|first25=L.|last26=Cai|first26=Q.|last27=Cardinali|first27=G.|last28=Chaverri|first28=P.|last29=Coppins|first29=B. J.|last30=Crespo|first30=A.|last31=Cubas|first31=P.|last32=Cummings|first32=C.|last33=Damm|first33=U.|last34=de Beer|first34=Z. W.|last35=de Hoog|first35=G. S.|last36=Del-Prado|first36=R.|last37=Dentinger|first37=B.|last38=Dieguez-Uribeondo|first38=J.|last39=Divakar|first39=P. K.|last40=Douglas|first40=B.|last41=Duenas|first41=M.|last42=Duong|first42=T. A.|last43=Eberhardt|first43=U.|last44=Edwards|first44=J. E.|last45=Elshahed|first45=M. S.|last46=Fliegerova|first46=K.|last47=Furtado|first47=M.|last48=Garcia|first48=M. A.|last49=Ge|first49=Z.-W.|last50=Griffith|first50=G. W.|last51=Griffiths|first51=K.|last52=Groenewald|first52=J. Z.|last53=Groenewald|first53=M.|last54=Grube|first54=M.|last55=Gryzenhout|first55=M.|last56=Guo|first56=L.-D.|last57=Hagen|first57=F.|last58=Hambleton|first58=S.|last59=Hamelin|first59=R. C.|last60=Hansen|first60=K.|last61=Harrold|first61=P.|last62=Heller|first62=G.|last63=Herrera|first63=C.|last64=Hirayama|first64=K.|last65=Hirooka|first65=Y.|last66=Ho|first66=H.-M.|last67=Hoffmann|first67=K.|last68=Hofstetter|first68=V.|last69=Hognabba|first69=F.|last70=Hollingsworth|first70=P. M.|last71=Hong|first71=S.-B.|last72=Hosaka|first72=K.|last73=Houbraken|first73=J.|last74=Hughes|first74=K.|last75=Huhtinen|first75=S.|last76=Hyde|first76=K. D.|last77=James|first77=T.|last78=Johnson|first78=E. M.|last79=Johnson|first79=J. E.|last80=Johnston|first80=P. R.|last81=Jones|first81=E. B. G.|last82=Kelly|first82=L. J.|last83=Kirk|first83=P. M.|last84=Knapp|first84=D. G.|last85=Koljalg|first85=U.|last86=Kovacs|first86=G. M.|last87=Kurtzman|first87=C. P.|last88=Landvik|first88=S.|last89=Leavitt|first89=S. D.|last90=Liggenstoffer|first90=A. S.|last91=Liimatainen|first91=K.|last92=Lombard|first92=L.|last93=Luangsa-ard|first93=J. J.|last94=Lumbsch|first94=H. T.|last95=Maganti|first95=H.|last96=Maharachchikumbura|first96=S. S. N.|last97=Martin|first97=M. P.|last98=May|first98=T. W.|last99=McTaggart|first99=A. R.|last100=Methven|first100=A. S.|last101=Meyer|first101=W.|last102=Moncalvo|first102=J.-M.|last103=Mongkolsamrit|first103=S.|last104=Nagy|first104=L. G.|last105=Nilsson|first105=R. H.|last106=Niskanen|first106=T.|last107=Nyilasi|first107=I.|last108=Okada|first108=G.|last109=Okane|first109=I.|last110=Olariaga|first110=I.|last111=Otte|first111=J.|last112=Papp|first112=T.|last113=Park|first113=D.|last114=Petkovits|first114=T.|last115=Pino-Bodas|first115=R.|last116=Quaedvlieg|first116=W.|last117=Raja|first117=H. A.|last118=Redecker|first118=D.|last119=Rintoul|first119=T. L.|last120=Ruibal|first120=C.|last121=Sarmiento-Ramirez|first121=J. M.|last122=Schmitt|first122=I.|last123=Schussler|first123=A.|last124=Shearer|first124=C.|last125=Sotome|first125=K.|last126=Stefani|first126=F. O. P.|last127=Stenroos|first127=S.|last128=Stielow|first128=B.|last129=Stockinger|first129=H.|last130=Suetrong|first130=S.|last131=Suh|first131=S.-O.|last132=Sung|first132=G.-H.|last133=Suzuki|first133=M.|last134=Tanaka|first134=K.|last135=Tedersoo|first135=L.|last136=Telleria|first136=M. T.|last137=Tretter|first137=E.|last138=Untereiner|first138=W. A.|last139=Urbina|first139=H.|last140=Vagvolgyi|first140=C.|last141=Vialle|first141=A.|last142=Vu|first142=T. D.|last143=Walther|first143=G.|last144=Wang|first144=Q.-M.|last145=Wang|first145=Y.|last146=Weir|first146=B. S.|last147=Weiss|first147=M.|last148=White|first148=M. M.|last149=Xu|first149=J.|last150=Yahr|first150=R.|last151=Yang|first151=Z. L.|last152=Yurkov|first152=A.|last153=Zamora|first153=J.-C.|last154=Zhang|first154=N.|last155=Zhuang|first155=W.-Y.|last156=Schindel|first156=D.|title=Nuclear ribosomal internal transcribed spacer (ITS) region as a universal DNA barcode marker for Fungi|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|date=27 March 2012|volume=109|issue=16|pages=6241–6246|doi=10.1073/pnas.1117018109|pmid=22454494|pmc=3341068}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Man|first1=S. M.|last2=Kaakoush|first2=N. O.|last3=Octavia|first3=S.|last4=Mitchell|first4=H.|title=The Internal Transcribed Spacer Region, a New Tool for Use in Species Differentiation and Delineation of Systematic Relationships within the Campylobacter Genus|journal=Applied and Environmental Microbiology|date=26 March 2010|volume=76|issue=10|pages=3071–3081|doi=10.1128/AEM.02551-09|pmid=20348308|pmc=2869123}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ranjard|first1=L.|last2=Poly|first2=F.|last3=Lata|first3=J.-C.|last4=Mougel|first4=C.|last5=Thioulouse|first5=J.|last6=Nazaret|first6=S.|title=Characterization of Bacterial and Fungal Soil Communities by Automated Ribosomal Intergenic Spacer Analysis Fingerprints: Biological and Methodological Variability|journal=Applied and Environmental Microbiology|date=1 October 2001|volume=67|issue=10|pages=4479–4487|doi=10.1128/AEM.67.10.4479-4487.2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bidet|first1=Philippe|last2=Barbut|first2=FrÃ©dÃ©ric|last3=Lalande|first3=ValÃ©rie|last4=Burghoffer|first4=BÃ©atrice|last5=Petit|first5=Jean-Claude|title=Development of a new PCR-ribotyping method for                            based on ribosomal RNA gene sequencing|journal=FEMS Microbiology Letters|date=June 1999|volume=175|issue=2|pages=261–266|doi=10.1111/j.1574-6968.1999.tb13629.x}}</ref>

===Medical research===

As highly conserved sequences often have important biological functions, they can be useful a starting point for identifying the cause of [[genetic disease]]s. Many [[Inborn error of metabolism|congenital metabolic disorders]] and [[Lysosomal storage disease]]s are the result of changes to individual conserved genes, resulting in missing or faulty enzymes that are the underlying cause of the symptoms of the disease. Genetic diseases may be predicted by identifying sequences that are conserved between humans and lab organisms such as [[laboratory mouse|mice]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ala |first1=Ugo |last2=Piro |first2=Rosario Michael |last3=Grassi |first3=Elena |last4=Damasco |first4=Christian |last5=Silengo |first5=Lorenzo |last6=Oti |first6=Martin |last7=Provero |first7=Paolo |last8=Di Cunto |first8=Ferdinando |last9=Tucker-Kellogg |first9=Greg |title=Prediction of Human Disease Genes by Human-Mouse Conserved Coexpression Analysis |journal=PLoS Computational Biology |date=28 March 2008 |volume=4 |issue=3 |pages=e1000043 |doi=10.1371/journal.pcbi.1000043|pmid=18369433 |pmc=2268251 }}</ref> or [[Drosophila melanogaster|fruit flies]],<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pandey |first1=U. B. |last2=Nichols |first2=C. D. |title=Human Disease Models in Drosophila melanogaster and the Role of the Fly in Therapeutic Drug Discovery |journal=Pharmacological Reviews |date=17 March 2011 |volume=63 |issue=2 |pages=411–436 |doi=10.1124/pr.110.003293|pmid=21415126 |pmc=3082451 }}</ref> and studying the effects of [[gene knockout|knock-outs]] of these genes.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Huang |first1=Hui |title=Evolutionary conservation and selection of human disease gene orthologs in the rat and mouse genomes |last2=Winter |first2=Eitan E |last3=Wang |first3=Huajun |last4=Weinstock |first4=Keith G |last5=Xing |first5=Heming |last6=Goodstadt |first6=Leo |last7=Stenson |first7=Peter D |last8=Cooper |first8=David N |last9=Smith |first9=Douglas |last10=Albà |first10=M Mar |last11=Ponting |first11=Chris P |last12=Fechtel |first12=Kim |journal=Genome Biology |date=2004 |volume=5 |issue=7 |pages=R47 |doi=10.1186/gb-2004-5-7-r47|pmid=15239832 |pmc=463309 }}</ref> [[Genome-wide association study|Genome-wide association studies]] can also be used to identify variation in conserved sequences associated with disease or health outcomes.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ge |first1=Dongliang |last2=Fellay |first2=Jacques |last3=Thompson |first3=Alexander J. |last4=Simon |first4=Jason S. |last5=Shianna |first5=Kevin V. |last6=Urban |first6=Thomas J. |last7=Heinzen |first7=Erin L. |last8=Qiu |first8=Ping |last9=Bertelsen |first9=Arthur H. |last10=Muir |first10=Andrew J. |last11=Sulkowski |first11=Mark |last12=McHutchison |first12=John G. |last13=Goldstein |first13=David B. |title=Genetic variation in IL28B predicts hepatitis C treatment-induced viral clearance |journal=Nature |date=16 August 2009 |volume=461 |issue=7262 |pages=399–401 |doi=10.1038/nature08309|pmid=19684573 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1093/hmg/ddp406 | pmid=19808789 | pmc=2758713 | volume=18 | issue=R2 | title=Genome-wide association studies in Alzheimer's disease | year=2009 | journal=Human Molecular Genetics | pages=R137–R145 | last1 = Bertram | first1 = L.}}</ref>

===Functional annotation===
Identifying conserved sequences can be used to discover and predict functional sequences such as genes.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kellis |first1=Manolis |last2=Patterson |first2=Nick |last3=Endrizzi |first3=Matthew |last4=Birren |first4=Bruce |last5=Lander |first5=Eric S. |title=Sequencing and comparison of yeast species to identify genes and regulatory elements |journal=Nature |date=15 May 2003 |volume=423 |issue=6937 |pages=241–254 |doi=10.1038/nature01644|pmid=12748633 }}</ref> Conserved sequences with a known function, such as protein domains, can also be used to predict the function of a sequence. Databases of conserved protein domains such as [[Pfam]] and the [[Conserved Domain Database]] can be used to annotate functional domains in predicted protein coding genes.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Marchler-Bauer |first1=A. |last2=Lu |first2=S. |last3=Anderson |first3=J. B. |last4=Chitsaz |first4=F. |last5=Derbyshire |first5=M. K. |last6=DeWeese-Scott |first6=C. |last7=Fong |first7=J. H. |last8=Geer |first8=L. Y. |last9=Geer |first9=R. C. |last10=Gonzales |first10=N. R. |last11=Gwadz |first11=M. |last12=Hurwitz |first12=D. I. |last13=Jackson |first13=J. D. |last14=Ke |first14=Z. |last15=Lanczycki |first15=C. J. |last16=Lu |first16=F. |last17=Marchler |first17=G. H. |last18=Mullokandov |first18=M. |last19=Omelchenko |first19=M. V. |last20=Robertson |first20=C. L. |last21=Song |first21=J. S.  |last22=Thanki |first22=N. |last23=Yamashita |first23=R. A. |last24=Zhang |first24=D. |last25=Zhang |first25=N. |last26=Zheng |first26=C. |last27=Bryant |first27=S. H. |title=CDD: a Conserved Domain Database for the functional annotation of proteins |journal=Nucleic Acids Research |date=24 November 2010 |volume=39 |issue=Database |pages=D225–D229 |doi=10.1093/nar/gkq1189|pmid=21109532 |pmc=3013737 }}</ref>

