{{Infobox Galaxy | name = Markarian 231 | image = Hubble Interacting Galaxy UGC 8058 (2008-04-24).jpg | image_size = 250px | credit = [[ESA]] | constellation name = [[Ursa Major]] | epoch = [[Epoch (astronomy)#Julian years and J2000|J2000]] | type = Sc/quasar | ra = {{RA|12||56|11}} | dec = {{DEC|+56|51|59}} | dist_ly = 581 [[light-year|Mly]] | z = 0.04147 | appmag_v =13.60 | size_v = | h_radial_v = | names = UGC 8058, Mrk 231, Mkn 231, Markarian 231, MCG+10-19-004, ZW VII 490, PGC 44117 | references = [http://simbad.u-strasbg.fr/simbad/sim-id?Ident=MRK+231 SIMBAD] }}
'''Markarian 231''' ('''UGC 8058''') is a Type-1 [[Seyfert galaxy]] that was discovered in 1969 as part of a search of galaxies with strong [[ultraviolet]] radiation. It contains the nearest known [[quasar]], and in 2015 it was shown that the powerful [[active galactic nucleus]] present in the center of the galaxy may in fact be a supermassive [[binary black hole]]. It is located about 581 million [[light years]] away from [[Earth]].
==Characteristics== The [[galaxy]] is now undergoing an energetic [[starburst galaxy|starburst]]. A nuclear ring of active star formation has been found in the center with a rate of formation greater than 100 [[solar masses]] per year. It is one of the most ultraluminous [[infrared]] galaxies with power derived from an accreting [[black hole]] in the center, and the closest known [[quasar]]. A 2015 study has found that the central black hole, estimated to be 150 million times the mass of our Sun, has a black hole companion weighing in at 4 million solar masses, and the duo completes an orbit around each other every 1.2 years.<ref>{{Cite web|title = HubbleSite - NewsCenter - Hubble Finds That the Nearest Quasar Is Powered by a Double Black Hole (08/27/2015) - The Full Story|url = http://hubblesite.org/newscenter/archive/releases/2015/31/full/|website = hubblesite.org|accessdate = 2015-08-27}}</ref> Subsequently, that model has been definitively shown to be unfeasible.<ref>http://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.3847/0004-637X/829/1/4/pdf</ref>
==See also== [[File:Artist's concept of double black hole.jpg|thumb|Artist's concept of double black hole.<ref>{{cite web|title=Artist's concept of double black hole|url=http://www.spacetelescope.org/images/opo1531a/|accessdate=31 August 2015}}</ref>]] *[[List of galaxies]]
